ent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel de Meaux was born in 1278, in Bishop Wilton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Walter De Meaux. She had at least 1 daughter with Lord Kexby Brian Burdon. She died in Wensleydale, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1278–":"1278–Surnud","1278–Female":"1278–Surnud","1280–1310":"1280–1310","–Male":"Surnud","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1295–1365":"1295–1365","1240–1265":"1240–1265","1278":"1278","1365":"1365","1332":"1332","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Wensleydale, Richmondshire district, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wensleydale, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gowthorpe Hall, Bishop Wilton, East Riding, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bishop Wilton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1278–":"1278–Kuollut","1278–Female":"1278–Kuollut","1280–1310":"1280–1310","–Male":"Kuollut","1270–1332":"1270–1332","129